04790nam a22007095i 9780813570242DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2013046604  a97808135702427 a10.36019/97808135702422doi  a(DE-B1597)526308  a(OCoLC)895661761  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHQ29b.M653 2014 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.70822231 aMontemurro, Beth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeserving Desire :bWomen's Stories of Sexual Evolution /cBeth Montemurro. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Developing a Stance: Sowing the Seeds of Sexual Subjectivity -- t3. Learning through Doing: Early Exploration and Experience -- t4. Validation, Affirmation, and Encouragement: Sexual Relationships of Consequence -- t5. Self-Discovery through Role and Relationship Changes: Divorce -- t6. Self-Discovery through Role and Relationship Changes: Motherhood -- t7. Self-Discovery through Embodied Changes: The Physical Experience of Motherhood -- t8. Self-Discovery through Embodied Changes: Aging and Menopause -- t9. Self-Acceptance: Staying Sexual Subjects -- tAppendix A: Demographic Characteristics of Research Participants -- tAppendix B: Methodology -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen experience considerable changes in their bodies, lives, and identity between the ages of twenty and seventy, including marriage, motherhood, the dissolution of relationships, and menopause, all of which often impact sexuality. In Deserving Desire, Beth Montemurro takes a wide-ranging look at the evolution of women’s sexuality over time, with a specific focus on the development of sexual subjectivity—that is sexual confidence, agency, and a sense of entitlement to sexual desire. Detailed stories of the ninety-five women in this study explore how they become more comfortable with their bodies, when most begin to enjoy sex, feel confident and positive about engaging in it, and how they become sexual subjects in control of their bodies. Deserving Desire explores the complex multi-stage process in which sexual subjectivity evolves over a woman’s lifetime. As girls, they learn about sex and how those around them—parents, peers, religion and media—regard sex. Physical and emotional transitions such as having a baby or ending a relationship further affect women’s sexual confidence and desire. Montemurro emphasizes that sexual subjectivity is about feeling in control of sexual decision making and acting purposefully and confidently. Though adolescent sexuality has been a major focus of sociological research, few studies have examined, as Montemurro does here, the development of sexuality through women’s lives and the events that change the way women feel about themselves, their bodies, and their relationships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSelf-acceptance. 0aWomenxPsychology. 0aWomenxSexual behavior. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357024240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813570242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813570242.jpg  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV